The Limit of Panic
Copenhagen—We often hear how the world we know will meet its end, typically through ecological collapse.
In fact, the basic idea has been with us since the Club of Rome's Limits to Growth, which was first published over forty years ago.
But time is not forgiving.
The Limits to Growth of 1972 warned humanity of an impending catastrophic collapse.
However, since then we have seen financial panics without any real shortages or production collapses.
On the contrary, the resources created by human ingenuity are more than sufficient to meet human consumption.
But the basic idea of Limits to Growth still holds: we continue on a trend, distracted by misleading solutions to minor issues while ignoring the big problems and wise solutions.
In the early 1970s, technological optimism waned, the Vietnam War became a disaster, societies fell into turmoil, and the economy stagnated.
Rachel Carson's 1962 book Silent Spring ignited fears about pollution and sparked the modern environmental movement; Paul Ehrlich's 1968 title The Population Bomb summed it up.
In the first Earth Day of 1970, there was widespread pessimism.
The aim of Limits to Growth was to make people worried about resource depletion.
This is our fate, because too many people want to consume too much.
Even with some time won for us by our genius, we will ultimately destroy the Earth and ourselves through pollution.
The only hope is to stagnate economic growth itself, reduce consumption, promote recycling, and encourage people to have fewer children, achieving social stability at significantly poorer levels than now.
This view still resonates, despite being fundamentally wrong.
For example, the authors of Limits to Growth predicted that the world would exhaust reserves of aluminum, copper, gold, lead, mercury, molybdenum, natural gas, oil, silver, tin, tungsten, and zinc before 2013.
However, while commodity prices have rebounded recently, they overall have fallen to about one-third of the level from 150 years ago.
Innovations replaced mercury in batteries, dental amalgams, and thermometers, and by 2000, mercury consumption had dropped by 98%, with prices falling by 90%.
More broadly, since 1946, supplies of copper, aluminum, iron, and zinc have exceeded demand, thanks to the discovery of new reserves and more economical new refining technologies.
Similarly, oil and natural gas were expected to be exhausted in 1990 and 1992, respectively; today, reserves of both are higher than in 1970, despite our consumption having increased significantly.
In the past six years, shale gas alone has doubled America's potential natural gas resources and halved their prices.
Regarding economic collapse, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change estimates that global per capita GDP will increase 14 times this century, with developing countries seeing a 24-fold increase.
The mistake in Limits to Growth was due to the authors overlooking the greatest resource of all: our own ingenuity.
Population growth began to slow down in the 1960s.
Food supply did not collapse (1.5 billion hectares of arable land are being used, with an additional 2.7 billion hectares in reserve).
The prevalence of malnutrition has been halved, dropping from 35% of the world's population to 16%.
Pollution did not pose a problem for us.
The Club of Rome imagined a pastoral past where we had no air pollution from particulates and were all happy farmers, while in the future, smokestacks from heating would make us unable to breathe. Reality is exactly the opposite.
In 1900, the global population was only 1.5 billion, yet nearly 3 million people died from air pollution each year—相当于每500人中就有一人—mostly indoor air pollution.
The mortality rate has dropped to one death per 2000 people.
Despite the number of deaths from pollution still being higher than those from malaria, the fatality rate is decreasing rather than increasing.
Despite this, the ideas fostered by The Limits to Growth continue to influence public and elite thinking.
Take recycling, for instance, it is usually just a feel-good gesture that is costly in terms of the environment and yields little benefit.
For example, paper typically comes from sustainable forests rather than tropical rainforests.
The procedures for paper recycling and government subsidies result in low-quality paper, while they protect resources that are not actually threatened.
Similarly, policies such as China's family planning and forced sterilization in India were driven by fears of overpopulation leading to self-destruction.
Moreover, although insecticides and other pollutants were believed to kill half of humanity, good regulation of insecticides resulted in only 20 deaths annually in the United States, while the use of insecticides created cheaper and more abundant food supplies.
In fact, relying solely on organic agriculture — the movement spurred by insecticide scares — would impose an additional annual cost of $100 billion on the United States.
Agricultural efficiency would decrease by 16%, requiring an additional 65 million hectares of farmland to maintain current output — an area equivalent to half the size of modern-day California.
Rising prices will lead to a decrease in fruit and vegetable consumption, resulting in severe negative health impacts, including an increase of tens of thousands of cancer deaths annually.
Being fixated on dark scenarios prevents us from addressing the real global threats.
Poverty is one of the biggest killers, claiming the lives of 15 million people annually — a quarter of all deaths.
The solution lies in economic growth.
When people lift themselves out of poverty, most can afford the burden of preventing infectious diseases.
In the past three decades, 680 million people in China have lifted themselves out of poverty, leading the world in reducing the number of贫困人口 by nearly 1 billion.
This has led to widespread improvements in health, lifespan, and quality of life.
The four decades since the publication of "Limits to Growth" have shown that we need more, not less, growth.
The expansion of trade is estimated to bring annual benefits exceeding $100 trillion by the end of this century, far surpassing the timid “good enough” policies fueled by fearmongering.
But this requires abandoning anti-growth思维 and harnessing our infinite potential to create a brighter future.
